AB  - One year ago, Emmanuel Farhi tragically passed away. Emmanuel was a prolific scholar, deep and versatile. Emmanuel epitomized the qualities that the Review of Economic Studies aspires to represent: he was a young researcher, combining theory and empirics, methodological and policy relevant contributions, appealing to a wide and heterogeneous audience. The trajectory of his career also parallels that of the Review: he was born and raised in Europe, quickly becoming one of the most influential economists worldwide.Emmanuel will be deeply missed, but his contributions will stay with us. He was close to the Review ever since he was invited to the Review Tour in 2006 and went on to publish seven papers in its pages. In this issue, we are proud to publish two more articles by Emmanuel, “Global Imbalances and Policy Wars at the Zero Lower Bound” joint with Ricardo Caballero and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas, and “Shadow Banking and the Four Pillars of Traditional Financial Intermediation” joint with Jean Tirole.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdab068
ER  - 



